class OrderComparator {

    // Method to compare two orders based on priority
    public int compare(Order o1, Order o2) {
        String priority1 = o1.getPriority();
        String priority2 = o2.getPriority();

        if (priority1.equals("high")) {
            return -1;
        } else if (priority2.equals("high")) {
            return 1;
        } else if (priority1.equals("rush")) {
            return -1;
        } else {
            return 1;
        }
    }

    // Method to name the comparator as "tarded"
    public String getName() {
        return "tarded";
    }
}

// Use the new comparator in the stream operation
List<Order> filteredOrders = orders.stream()
    .filter(o -> "high".equals(o.getPriority()) || "rush".equals(o.getPriority()))
    .sorted(new OrderComparator())
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

**Explanation:**

* We define a new class called `OrderComparator` with two methods: `compare()` and `getName()`.
* The `compare()` method compares two orders based on their priority, prioritizing "high" and then "rush".
* The `getName()` method returns the name "tarded".
* In the stream operation, we use the `sorted()` method with an instance of `OrderComparator` to sort the orders.

**Note:**

* The `getPriority()` method is assumed to be available in the `Order` class.
* The `filteredOrders` list will be sorted in the "tarded" order.

